responded: The root cause of the bug is that `space->select.sel_info.hslab` can be NULL, but the code in `H5S__get_select_hyper_blocklist` dereferences it without checking. The sanitizer report and the stack trace point to this dereference, and the function `H5Sget_select_hyper_blocklist` does not check for this condition either.

A correct patch should:
- Add a check for `space->select.sel_info.hslab == NULL` in both `H5Sget_select_hyper_blocklist` and `H5S__get_select_hyper_blocklist`.
- Return an error code if this is the case, before any dereference.

This avoids a NULL pointer dereference and is in line with the error handling style of the code.

Here is the patch:

```diff
--- a/src/H5Shyper.c
+++ b/src/H5Shyper.c
@@ -4656,6 +4656,10 @@
     assert(space);
     assert(buf);
-    assert(space->select.sel_info.hslab->unlim_dim < 0);
+    if (space->select.sel_info.hslab == NULL)
+        return FAIL;
+    assert(space->select.sel_info.hslab->unlim_dim < 0);

     /* Attempt to rebuild diminfo if it is invalid and has not been confirmed
      * to be impossible.
@@ -4847,6 +4847,10 @@
     if (space->select.sel_info.hslab->unlim_dim >= 0)
         HGOTO_ERROR(H5E_DATASPACE, H5E_UNSUPPORTED, FAIL, "cannot get blocklist for unlimited selection");
+    if (space->select.sel_info.hslab == NULL)
+        HGOTO_ERROR(H5E_ARGS, H5E_BADVALUE, FAIL, "no hyperslab selection info");

     /* Go get the correct number of blocks */
     if (numblocks > 0)
         ret_value = H5S__get_select_hyper_blocklist(space, startblock, numblocks, buf);
     else
         ret_value = SUCCEED; /* Successfully got 0 blocks... */
```

